S.Africa, Canada Sign Justice Aid Agreement 
An Agreement under which the canadian government will provide at least
4.5 million U.S. Dollars to help upgrade South Africa's judicial system
was signed today in Cape Town.
Justice minister Dullah Omar, who signed for the South African
government, said the money will fund South Africa's systematic training
program for judges, magistrates, prosecutors and administrative
personnel, reported the South African Press Association.
Under the agreement, Canada will provide technical and financial aid to
South Africa over the next four years.
Omar said South Africa had a great deal to learn from Canada in
strengthening and ensuring the independence of the judiciary, and in
managing court systems.
Canadian Deputy Justice Minister George Thomson said the agreement
marks the beginning of a strong and positive working relationship
between the two countries.
